'''Erik Huggers''' is a media executive currently serving as CEO of video hosting service [[Vevo]].<ref name=variety-huggers-becomes-ceo>{{cite web|url = http://variety.com/2015/digital/exec-shuffle-people-news/vevo-erik-huggers-ceo-1201484424/|title = Vevo Names Erik Huggers CEO|last = Spangler|first = Todd|publisher = ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''|date = April 30, 2015|accessdate = August 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=billboard-huggers-becomes-ceo>{{Cite web|url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6553072/vevo-appoints-erik-huggers-as-new-ceo|title = Vevo Appoints Erik Huggers as New CEO|date = April 30, 2015|accessdate = August 20, 2017|publisher = ''[[Billboard]]''}}</ref> He previously worked at [[Microsoft]],<ref name=billboard-huggers-becomes-ceo/><ref name=variety-huggers-becomes-ceo/><ref name=guardian-huggers-leaves-bbc/> [[Endemol]],<ref name=billboard-huggers-becomes-ceo/><ref name=variety-huggers-becomes-ceo/><ref name=guardian-huggers-leaves-bbc/> the [[BBC]],<ref name=guardian-huggers-leaves-bbc/> and at OnCue, [[Intel]]'s Internet TV effort that was acquired by [[Verizon]].<ref name=forbes-verizon-buys-oncue/>

== Early life and education ==

Huggers hails from the [[Netherlands]].<ref name=ft-huggers-vevo-interview>{{cite web|url = https://www.ft.com/content/37fda620-e7de-11e6-893c-082c54a7f539|title = Erik Huggers of Vevo on capturing audiences in a crowded market. The music video streaming service wants to convince teenagers to pay|last = Nicolau|first = Anna|date = February 26, 2017|accessdate = August 20, 2017|publisher = ''[[Financial Times]]''}}</ref>

== Career ==

=== Microsoft and Endemol ===

Huggers has worked in managerial roles at [[Microsoft]] and [[Endemol]].<ref name=billboard-huggers-becomes-ceo/><ref name=variety-huggers-becomes-ceo/><ref name=guardian-huggers-leaves-bbc/>

=== BBC ===

Huggers joined the [[BBC]] in May 2007, and was appointed director of the future, media and technology arm in August 2008, replacing [[Ashley Highfield]].<ref name=guardian-huggers-leaves-bbc>{{cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jan/18/erik-huggers-bbc-intel|title = Erik Huggers to leave BBC for Intel. Director of future, media and technology will join US computer firm as corporate vice-president|last = Halliday|first = Josh|date = January 18, 2011|accessdate = August 20, 2017|publisher = ''[[The Guardian]]''}}</ref><ref name=ft-huggers-leaves-bbc>{{cite web|url = https://www.ft.com/content/b4fbe7fb-3255-33a3-9b62-22d573ba709b|title = Erik Huggers on changing the BBC|publisher = ''[[Financial Times]]''|date = January 24, 2011|accessdate = August 20, 2017|last = Bradshaw|first = Tim}}</ref> Huggers was credited with bringing order amidst chaos and feudal infighting, helped by his outside perspective, while at the same time causing discontent among people for his macho attitude, leading to many who were happy to see his leave.<ref name=guardian-huggers-bbc-legacy>{{cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/media/pda/2011/jan/20/bbc-erik-huggers-ralph-rivera|title = BBC Future Media: What is Erik Huggers' legacy? Huggers can take credit for destroying the culture of chaos and feuding in the BBC's technology wing, insiders say. But what now?|last = Kiss|first = Jemima|date = January 21, 2011|accessdate = August 20, 2017|publisher = ''[[The Guardian]]''}}</ref>

Huggers was also the subject of controversy when he submitted reimbursement requests for taxi rides for thousands of pounds, including £639 for a single day of taxi rides.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/feb/09/bbc-expenses-huggers-taxis|title = How do you spend £639 on a taxi? Ask the BBC's technology chief. Silicon Valley and Las Vegas provide backdrop for limousine journeys by BBC whizz behind the iPlayer|last = Addley|first = Esther|date = February 9, 2010|accessdate = August 20, 2017|publisher = ''[[The Guardian]]''}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/7610499/Three-BBC-executives-spend-12000-on-taxis.html|title = Three BBC executives spend £12,000 on taxis. A trio of BBC executives ran up more than £12,000 in taxi claims on expenses between them in a three-month period, new figures showed.|publisher = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''|date = April 20, 2010|accessdate = August 20, 2017}}</ref>

Huggers' departure was announced in January 2011,<ref name=guardian-huggers-leaves-bbc/><ref name=ft-huggers-leaves-bbc/> and his role was split into two, with John Linwood taking over technology and Ralph Rivera taking over digital media.<ref name=guardian-huggers-bbc-legacy/>

=== Intel (OnCue) and Verizon ===

After leaving the BBC, Huggers became corporate vice-president and general manager of the digital home group of chip maker [[Intel]].<ref name=guardian-huggers-leaves-bbc/> In that role, he led OnCue, Intel's Internet TV effort.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://thenextweb.com/media/2013/02/12/intel-is-building-an-internet-tv-service-with-a-camera-sporting-set-top-box-platform-to-launch-within-a-year/|title = Intel is building an Internet TV service with a camera-sporting set-top box; platform to launch within a year|last = Protalinski|first = Emil|date = February 12, 2013|accessdate = August 20, 2017|publisher = ''The Next Web''}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.reuters.com/article/us-intel-tv-idUSBRE91B1C420130212|title = Intel plans online TV service as PC chip sales wane|last = Randewich|first = Noel|last2 = Grover|first2 = Ronald|date = February 12, 2013|accessdate = August 20, 2017|publisher = [[Reuters]]}}</ref>

In January 2014, it was announced that [[Verizon]] was acquiring OnCue, and Huggers would become a senior vice president at Verizon.<ref name=forbes-verizon-buys-oncue>{{cite web|url = https://www.forbes.com/sites/patrickmoorhead/2014/01/21/verizon-buys-intel-media-and-oncue-creating-a-large-opportunity/#7cc0357b1054|title = Verizon Buys Intel Media And OnCue Creating A Large Opportunity|publisher = ''[[Forbes]]''|last = Moorhead|first = Patrick|date = January 21, 2014|accessdate = August 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://thenextweb.com/media/2014/03/19/oncue-verizon-erik-huggers/|title = Inside OnCue: The story behind Verizon’s Internet TV acquisition|date = March 19, 2014|accessdate = August 20, 2017|publisher = ''The Next Web''|last = Sawers|first = Paul}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://techcrunch.com/2014/01/21/verizon-ramps-up-tv-ambitions-buys-oncue-and-the-rest-of-intel-media-from-intel/|title = Verizon Ramps Up In TV, Buys Troubled OnCue And The Rest Of Intel Media From Intel|last = Lunden|first = Ingrid|date = January 21, 2014|accessdate = August 20, 2017|publisher = ''[[TechCrunch]]''}}</ref>

=== Vevo ===

In late April, 2015, it was announced that Huggers was joining video hosting service [[Vevo]] as CEO, taking over from Rio Caraeff, Vevo's founding CEO, who left at the end of 2014.<ref name=variety-huggers-becomes-ceo/><ref name=billboard-huggers-becomes-ceo/><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.recode.net/2015/4/29/11562046/former-intel-web-tv-boss-erik-huggers-is-vevos-new-ceo|title = Former Intel Web TV Boss Erik Huggers Is Vevo's New CEO. His old job -- trying to launch a Web TV service -- was hard. This one will be, too.|last = Kafka|first = Peter|date = April 29, 2015|accessdate = August 20, 2017|publisher = ''Recode''}}</ref> Huggers works from Vevo's [[New York City]] headquarters.<ref name=ft-huggers-vevo-interview/>

In his role as CEO, Huggers initially planned to focus on launching a paid subscription.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/can-vevo-find-model-works-make-music-business-rich/|title = CAN VEVO FIND A MODEL THAT WORKS – AND MAKE THE MUSIC BUSINESS RICH?|last = Ingham|first = Tim|publisher = Music Business Worldwide|date = November 22, 2016|accessdate = August 20, 2017}}</ref> However, he deferred that goal in order to focus on international expansion of its localized website and apps, to better cater to the 80% of its users who were accessing its content from outside the United States (mostly through partners such as [[YouTube]]).<ref>{{cite web|url = http://variety.com/2017/digital/news/vevo-subscription-international-expansion-erik-huggers-1201980357/|title = Vevo to Postpone Subscription Launch, Focus on International Expansion|last = Roettgers|first = Janko|date = February 7, 2017|accessdate = August 20, 2017|publisher = ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''}}</ref><ref name=ft-huggers-vevo-interview/> Huggers has identified as one of his main challenges making people aware of and engaged with the Vevo brand directly; as of now the majority of views of Vevo videos happen on the [[YouTube]] platform.<ref name=ft-huggers-vevo-interview/>

